        Official Singles Chart on 17/7/2020

        17 July 2020 - 23 July 2020

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (17/07/2020 - 23/07/2020)

        Honestly, looking through this new chart, it’s not much different from last week at all! I mean, the biggest takeover as a result of a new album was a posthumous release for an upcoming American rapper that died way before their time, some other American & British urban music debuting lower down, as well as the focus elsewhere being on a couple of EDM newcomers.

        What’s also not changing is ‘Savage Love’ at #1! That being said, its time at the top might be a bit more limited than I first thought. I mean, I can’t see that it’s currently dominant in any one format & it’s lost a surprising amount of radio momentum too!

        Of course, I’m not about to complain when the song that’s on course to take its title is the 10/10 smash that is ‘Head & Heart’! Not only is it extremely rare to see EDM songs reach the Top 3 in their second week in 2020, but it’s also leapfrogged ‘Savage Love’ on airplay, while also out in front on iTunes & Apple Music by a considerable margin.

        Hopefully we can celebrate that going to the top next week, however, once again, there are a few new arrivals to deal with before we can even start to think about that!

        Now, the big story of this week are the tributes to Juice WRLD, which allowed him to land the three highest debuts of the week! As usual, because they’re effectively caused by an album bomb, I’ll try to keep the track reviews a bit shorter here. Anyway, we’re starting off on a really strong note, as the highest charting of all the tracks is also the best one on the album! Juice WRLD’s slower, soulful & more chilled delivery makes him sound a lot like Post Malone on this one; an artist I’ve really grown to like over the years! That being said, being an EDM fan, I adore Marshmello’s part too. I feel he’s been taking a more rock approach with his discography & it’s not much different here with the grungy guitar riffs! They do feel a bit abrupt in the first verse, but the build-up & especially the drop in the second gives this song the energy it needs. Honestly, if Juice WRLD had made more music when he was alive, I might actually have checked out more of his music, because this is very impressive! Light 9/10 for ‘Come & Go’.

        Then there’s ‘Life’s A Mess’ with Halsey, which takes a much more serious & gentle tone! The production might be incredibly faint here until the slightly distorted & fuzzy hook, but I’ve got to admire Juice WRLD’s sincerity here. See, this is where rappers making deep content actually stands out to me! Besides, Juice WRLD is the only reason that ‘Without Me’ was tolerable (sorry Coolocelot!), but this time, I actually wish we heard more of Halsey here. She sounds amazing, but her breathy & angelic vocals don’t get enough recognition until the very end of the song! Those strings in the end are also really heart-hitting, especially for his die-hard fans. Again, this was better than expected, so I’m giving it a strong 7/10!

        The last Juice WRLD entry today is ‘Wishing Well’... can he make it three out of three for me? Eh, okay, I’ll give him a pass for this, but it’s not one of the highlights of the album for me! I’ve actually seen people link this to ‘Robbery’ given Juice WRLD’s wailing delivery & while they’re not exactly wrong (this is still by far the biggest issue with this song!), he’s at least showing a lot more passion here. In fact, with the bubbly yet gentle trap beat, this was constructed in a way that allows the listener to focus on Juice WRLD himself more! I’m glad they did though, because man, the lyrics hit hard here & I imagine it’s one of the hardest songs emotionally for people who were close to him to listen to. The fact that he’s frustrated but determined to turn his live around shows how hard he was truly fighting to overcome his drug attention & he references this elsewhere in the content, showing incredible self-awareness, even during such a tough time! He knows what he's doing is wrong, but he wants to make it right. While this song isn’t going to bring him back to life, I’d like to think it can help save the lives of others going through the same thing as him! Yeah, despite what I’ve been told about this from others, this is a massive improvement over ‘Robbery’. I’m not sure this is going to stick around like the other two songs of his I just reviewed unfortunately, but it’s still not bad though, so I’m thinking a strong 6/10! No surprises that he took the #1 album this week. Most importantly though, RIP Juice WRLD!

        Hey, even though his album came out last week, it would appear that we’re not done with Pop Smoke, because ‘Mood Swings’ apparently had enough consistency to sneak into this chart! As you might remember, I was kind of indifferent on ‘Shoot For The Stars’ as a whole & I haven’t heard enough of Lil Tjay to have much of an opinion on him, so I thought it was best to go in without expectations here… but man, this ended up being fairly positive as a whole. Some critics have actually made 50 Cent comparisons here, to which I actually kind of agree with, especially when Pop Smoke steps away from rapping & sings on the hook! Lil Tjay is a fine enough fit, but I don’t think he has enough presence to truly hold up over this old-school, laid-back production. That being said, while it doesn’t seem like it’ll have very high replay factor, I will say that I’m surprised it didn’t chart last week! I’m giving this a strong 6/10.

        Fine, let’s get the new D-Block Europe song out of the way next! Unsurprisingly, given the number of times this group has disappointed me, I only heard it for the first time during the chart show on Radio 1 today. Anyway, my thoughts after hearing this is that it’s just more disposable than outright bad! Their use of a really muddy trap beat isn’t exactly revolutionary, with the most interesting production feature being the more sinister bass that comes in a bit later on, as it at least gives this song a bit more substance. That being said, it doesn’t add much when both artists are slathered in autotune & talking about all the girls they’ve got with! At least their lyrics are a bit more open about the struggles they faced on the streets, but unfortunately, I get the feeling that I’m going to forget this one even exists by the time the weekend’s over & given the number of low charting entries this duo have, it’s going to be a monthly duty covering their songs at this point… joy. Why couldn’t the new Kid Cudi & Eminem collaboration have made it instead? As for this, light 4/10!

        Anyway, I’ve saved a club banger for last again, as ‘Fake Friends’ finally makes its long overdue entrance! I’ve actually got two people to thank for this; 1) Riley, for always being observant of new upcoming bangers & 2) Capital FM playing this almost on an hourly basis! Anyway, I say “thank”, because I’ve been obsessed with this one for a while now, haha. I like the sudden burst of euphoria with that rousing piano melody, along with Alex's commentary on her fake friends, as well as the perception that their lives are better than hers! However, while the content might sound incredibly serious, the chorus is extremely addictive (mainly thanks to that vocal hook), but it’s the blazing bass tucked in beneath all of that makes this an immediate party anthem. I don’t know if it’ll hold up with the very best EDM hits of 2020, but given how fun & fresh it sounds, this is still a highly credible effort! Strong 8/10.

        Speaking of new dance songs, it’s cool to see ‘Dancing In The Moonlight’ moving closer to the Top 20, but outside of that, I’m not too happy to see ‘Rover’ hit ACR. I honestly thought the latter would’ve been #1 for at least a week!

        As for next week, it could be an interesting one, as Kygo attempts to revive another 80s classic following the success of ‘Higher Love’, Anne-Marie & Doja Cat team up on a new song, DJ Khaled returns out of nowhere & Ellie Goulding releases her first studio album in five years.

        Until then, I hope you all have a good week ahead! :)

        EDIT: Yes, I know I forgot to fully review 'B1llionz', but that just shows you how immediately forgettable this song is. Not even the slightly groovy drill beat can save the whole song from sounding a mess, especially with M1llion's hollow flow & those incredibly irritating chipmunk vocals. Strong 2/10 for this one!

        ⁉️
